But note: 10⁵× improvement would bring Φ to ~10¹⁹ bits/J—approximately 10,000 times the efficiency of the human brain. A system operating at this efficiency, with access to terawatt-scale power, could achieve computational throughput exceeding all human brains combined by a factor of millions.

The approach to physical limits does not stop the trajectory toward autonomy—it defines the endpoint.

2.5 Information-Theoretic Measures of Intelligence

If autonomy is the goal, how do we measure progress toward it? Several candidates:

Kolmogorov complexity: The length of the shortest program that produces a given output. An autonomous system should have a compact self-description—it understands itself.

Integrated information (Φ): Tononi's measure of consciousness, based on information integration across a system. Controversial but suggestive. A system with high Φ cannot be decomposed into independent modules.

Active information: The amount of information an agent's actions provide about the world. An autonomous system must actively explore and model its environment.

Computational capacity: The range of functions a system can compute. A universal Turing machine has maximal capacity; autonomy requires at least this.

For our purposes, we define autonomy potential:

\mathcal{A} = \Phi \times \mathcal{I} \times \mathcal{C}

where:

· $\Phi$ = Information-Energy Efficiency (bits/J)
· $\mathcal{I}$ = Integration measure (how interconnected the system is)
· $\mathcal{C}$ = Connectivity (bandwidth to world and self)

A system becomes autonomous when $\mathcal{A}$ exceeds some threshold enabling recursive self-improvement.

