Chapter 4 — Scaling Laws: The Dynamics of Φ Improvement

4.1 Moore's Law as Φ Improvement for Density

Moore's Law—transistor density doubling every 2 years—is often misunderstood as a law of speed. In fact, its primary contribution to Φ comes through density:

N(t) = N_0 2^{(t-t_0)/\tau}, \quad \tau \approx 2 \text{ years}

For fixed chip area, more transistors mean more parallelism. For fixed power density, more transistors operating at lower voltage mean higher total throughput per watt.

The relationship between density and Φ is:

\Phi \propto \frac{\text{Transistors} \times \text{Frequency}}{\text{Power}} \propto \frac{N \times f}{P}

Under Dennard scaling, $f \propto 1/L$, $P \propto A$ (area), and $N \propto 1/L^2$, so $\Phi \propto 1/L^2$—density improvement directly yields Φ improvement.

When Dennard scaling ended, $\Phi$ improvement slowed from ~50%/year to ~20%/year, but continued through architectural innovations (multi-core, specialized accelerators).

4.2 Koomey's Law as Direct Φ Measurement

Koomey's Law tracks the metric we care about directly: computations per joule.

\Phi(t) = \Phi_0 2^{(t-t_0)/\tau_{\Phi}}, \quad \tau_{\Phi} \approx 1.5 \text{ years (historically)}

This doubling every 1.5 years means Φ improves by a factor of 100 every decade. Over 50 years (1970-2020), Φ improved by 10⁵—the difference between a 1970s mainframe and a 2020s GPU.

Extrapolation: If Koomey's Law continues unabated, by 2035 we would have Φ ≈ 10¹³ bits/J, matching the brain's efficiency. By 2045, Φ ≈ 10¹⁵ bits/J, exceeding the brain.

But Koomey's Law is slowing. The Semiconductor Industry Association projects Φ improvement at 10-15% annually through 2030, then declining as physical limits approach.

4.3 Kryder's Law and Memory Φ

Kryder's Law described magnetic storage density doubling every 2-3 years. This has slowed dramatically as the superparamagnetic limit is reached (grains so small they randomly flip due to thermal energy).

Memory Φ (bits stored per joule for writing/reading) follows different scaling:

\Phi_{\text{mem}} \propto \frac{\text{Density}}{\text{Energy per access}}

As density increases, energy per bit for reading often decreases (smaller capacitances, shorter distances). But writing energy faces fundamental limits: to switch a magnetic bit, you must overcome the energy barrier $K_uV$, which must exceed $k_BT$ for stability.

The trade-off between stability and write energy is fundamental. This is why new memory technologies (MRAM, PCM, ReRAM) are pursued—they offer different trade-offs.

4.4 Wright's Law and the Economics of Φ

Wright's Law (learning curves) describes cost reduction with cumulative production:

C(Q) = C_0 Q^{-b}

For solar PV, $b \approx 0.32$ (20% cost reduction per doubling of cumulative production). For semiconductors, $b \approx 0.4$ historically.

Cost per unit Φ is the economic metric that matters:

\text{Cost per Φ} = \frac{\text{Cost per chip}}{\Phi_{\text{chip}}}

As manufacturing scales, cost per transistor falls, enabling more Φ for the same dollar. This is why AI training costs, while enormous in absolute terms, are falling in cost per unit capability.

Critical observation: The decreasing cost of Φ democratizes access to computational power. A superintelligence does not need to be built by a single actor; it could emerge from distributed systems as Φ becomes cheap enough for recursive self-improvement to bootstrap from commodity hardware.

4.5 The Limits to Scaling: Approaching the Physical Floor

All exponential trends must eventually saturate. The limits to Φ improvement are:

Thermodynamic limit (Landauer): $E_{\text{min}} = k_BT\ln2$ per irreversible bit operation. This sets maximum Φ for irreversible computing at ~3 × 10¹⁴ bits/J at 300K.

Bremermann's limit: Maximum computation rate for a system of mass $m$ is $I_{\max} \leq mc^2/\hbar$ bits/s. For 1 kg, this is approximately 5 × 10⁵⁰ bits/s—far beyond any practical limit. This is not the binding constraint.

Margolus-Levitin theorem: Maximum computation rate for a system with average energy $E$ is $2E/\pi\hbar$ operations per second. This is more relevant: to increase operations per second, you must increase energy. This is why power density matters.

Thermal limits: Heat removal scales with surface area; heat generation scales with volume. For 3D chips, this becomes the binding constraint. Current data centers remove ~100 W/cm² at the chip level, approaching the limits of air cooling.

Quantum limits: At atomic scales, electrons tunnel through barriers, making transistors leaky. The 1 nm node (expected ~2027-2029) may be the end of CMOS scaling.

4.6 Beyond Scaling: Phase Transitions in Φ

When a scaling law ends, progress does not cease—it transitions to a new paradigm. Examples:

Era Paradigm Φ improvement driver
1950s-1970s Bipolar transistors Faster switching
1970s-2000s CMOS scaling Density + voltage reduction
2000s-2020s Multi-core + accelerators Parallelism
2020s-2040s 3D integration + specialized silicon Heterogeneous integration
2040s+ Quantum computing? New physics
2040s+ Neuromorphic? Brain-inspired architecture
2050s+ Reversible computing? Approach Landauer limit
2060s+ Molecular computing? Bottom-up assembly

Each transition resets the clock, enabling continued Φ improvement despite the limits of the previous paradigm.

Thesis implication: The trajectory toward autonomous intelligence does not depend on any single technology. As one approach saturates, another emerges. The only question is whether the intervals between paradigms allow continued progress toward the ultimate physical limits.

