Chapter 8 — Nuclear Energy: The High-Density Path

8.1 The Binding Energy Revolution

Nuclear energy derives from the strong force binding nucleons. The binding energy per nucleon peaks at iron-56 (8.8 MeV). Lighter nuclei release energy when fused; heavier nuclei release energy when split.

The mass-energy equivalence ($E = mc^2$) means that even small mass defects yield enormous energy. Compare:

Fuel Energy per kg (MJ) Energy per kg (relative to chemical) CO₂ per MWh (g)
Gasoline 46 1× ~800
Coal 24 0.5× ~1000
Natural gas 54 1.2× ~500
Uranium-235 (fission) $3.9 \times 10^9$ 85 million× ~10 (lifecycle)
Deuterium-tritium (fusion) $9.4 \times 10^{10}$ 2 billion× ~0

This staggering density means:

· Fuel transport is trivial (a year's fuel for a 1 GW reactor fits in a truck)
· Waste volume is small (but hazardous)
· Land use per MWh is minimal
· Energy security is high (no fuel dependence)

8.2 Fission: The Demonstrated Technology

Nuclear fission splits heavy nuclei (uranium-235, plutonium-239) into lighter fragments plus neutrons. A typical fission releases ~200 MeV per event.

The chain reaction requires neutrons to cause further fissions. The effective neutron multiplication factor $k$ determines behavior:

· $k < 1$: Subcritical (decays)
· $k = 1$: Critical (steady)
· $k > 1$: Supercritical (exponential growth)

Reactor control uses neutron-absorbing control rods to maintain $k = 1$.

Fission's contribution to Φ: A 1 GWe nuclear plant running at 90% capacity factor generates approximately $7.9 \times 10^{15}$ J/year. At $\Phi_{\text{computing}} = 10^{12}$ bits/J, this could support $7.9 \times 10^{27}$ bits/year of computation—approximately 10¹⁰ times current global data center throughput.

Thesis implication: A single large nuclear plant could power the computational equivalent of thousands of human brains. Fission already provides the energy density necessary for any conceivable terrestrial AI. The barrier is not energy but engineering, regulation, and public acceptance.

8.3 The Fission Challenges

Safety: Chernobyl (RBMK design flaw + operator error) and Fukushima (tsunami exceeding design basis) have created public fear. Modern designs (Generation III+ and IV) incorporate passive safety—they shut down without operator action or power.

Waste: High-level waste requires isolation for 10,000+ years. Volume is small (all US nuclear waste ever generated would cover a football field ~10 yards deep), but political solutions for permanent disposal remain elusive.

Proliferation: Enrichment and reprocessing technologies can produce weapons-usable material. This constrains international deployment.

Economics: Nuclear capital costs have escalated dramatically (from ~$1000/kW in 1970s to ~$6000-9000/kW today in Western countries). Long construction times (5-10 years) and regulatory uncertainty make financing difficult.

8.4 The Promise of Advanced Fission

Generation IV designs address many limitations:

Molten salt reactors: Fuel dissolved in molten fluoride salt. Passive safety (drain tank if overheated), continuous reprocessing, high temperature for industrial heat.

Fast reactors: No moderator, use fast neutrons. Can "burn" actinides (reducing waste toxicity) and breed fuel (convert U-238 to Pu-239). Closed fuel cycle extracts ~100× more energy from uranium.

Small modular reactors (SMRs): Factory-built, transportable, scalable from 10-300 MWe. Lower upfront capital, shorter construction, siting flexibility.

Microreactors: 1-20 MWe, transportable by truck, factory-fabricated, autonomous operation. Ideal for remote communities, military bases, and—significantly—dedicated power for large computational facilities.

Critical observation: Microreactors could provide dedicated, secure power for an autonomous AI facility. With autonomous operation (minimal human oversight), the AI could potentially control its own power source—a significant step toward energy autonomy.

8.5 Fusion: The Asymptotic Goal

Fusion combines light nuclei to form heavier ones. The easiest reaction is deuterium-tritium:

D + T \rightarrow ^4\text{He} (3.5 \text{ MeV}) + n (14.1 \text{ MeV})

The Lawson criterion for ignition requires:

n\tau > \frac{12}{E_{\text{ch}}} \frac{k_B T}{\langle \sigma v \rangle}

For D-T fusion, this is approximately $n\tau > 10^{20}$ s/m³ at $T \approx 10$ keV (100 million K).

Approaches:

Method Concept Leading projects Status
Magnetic confinement Tokamak, stellarator ITER, SPARC, Wendelstein 7-X ITER aiming for Q=10 by 2035
Inertial confinement Lasers compress pellet NIF (USA), LMJ (France) NIF achieved ignition (Q~1.5) in 2022
Magnetic target fusion Magnetically compressed plasma General Fusion Experimental
Electrostatic Fusors, polywell Private companies Far from breakeven

Fusion's contribution to Φ: If achieved, fusion offers:

· Fuel from seawater (deuterium) and lithium (tritium breeding)
· No long-lived waste (structure becomes activated, but decay times ~100 years)
· No meltdown risk (plasma disrupts, reaction stops)
· High temperature for efficient thermal conversion

A 1 GWe fusion plant would consume ~100 kg of deuterium per year—virtually unlimited fuel.

8.6 Nuclear and the Kardashev Scale

Kardashev Type I civilization requires ~10¹⁶ W—approximately 10,000 times current human consumption. To achieve this:

Source Power density (W/m²) Land required for 10¹⁶ W Feasibility
Solar ~5-10 (average) 1-2 million km² Possible, but huge land use
Wind ~1-2 5-10 million km² Impractical
Fission ~500-1000 (reactor + exclusion) 10,000-20,000 km² Feasible
Fusion ~500-1000 (projected) 10,000-20,000 km² Feasible if achieved

Thesis implication: Only nuclear (fission or fusion) can power Kardashev Type I civilization without covering the planet in collectors. If the trajectory toward autonomous intelligence requires Type I energy scales—for space settlement, planetary-scale computation, or post-biological intelligence—then nuclear is essential.

