Critical observation: The trend is toward specialization. General-purpose CPUs are being supplemented by accelerators for specific workloads—GPUs for graphics and AI, TPUs for neural networks, DPUs for networking. An autonomous system might combine many specialized processors, each optimized for different aspects of cognition.

12.6 The Physical Limits of CMOS

As transistors shrink to atomic dimensions, fundamental limits appear:

Gate oxide tunneling: Below ~1 nm thickness, electrons tunnel through the oxide, causing leakage current. High-κ dielectrics (hafnium-based) extend this limit, but not indefinitely.

Channel length: Below ~3 nm, source and drain are so close that the gate cannot fully control the channel—short-channel effects degrade switching.

Dopant variability: At small dimensions, the discrete nature of dopant atoms means each transistor has slightly different threshold voltage, causing timing and power variations.

Quantum confinement: In extremely thin channels, energy levels become quantized, altering device behavior.

Thermal limits: Power density in modern CPUs (100-200 W/cm²) approaches that of a nuclear reactor core. Further scaling requires either lower voltage (which increases leakage) or better cooling (which has limits).

The end of Dennard scaling (around 2005) meant voltage stopped scaling with dimensions. This ended the era of ever-increasing clock speeds. Since then, progress has come from:

· Multi-core processors: More cores instead of faster cores
· Specialized accelerators: GPUs, TPUs, FPGAs
· 3D integration: Stacking chips vertically
· Advanced packaging: Chiplets, interposers
· Near-threshold computing: Operating at very low voltage for efficiency
· Advanced nodes: TSMC 3nm (Nvidia Rubin) with 336B transistors 

Thesis implication: The end of classical scaling does not mean the end of Φ improvement. It means a shift to architectural and packaging innovations—and eventually, to new computing paradigms (quantum, neuromorphic, reversible).

