16.2 The Bandwidth to Host a Mind: The Crossover Equation

What bandwidth would be required to integrate a distributed intelligence? Consider the human brain's internal communication:

· Neurons: ~10¹¹
· Synapses per neuron: ~10⁴
· Spike rate: ~10 Hz
· Bits per spike: ~1 (if rate coding, though temporal coding could increase this)

Total internal bandwidth: ~10¹¹ × 10⁴ × 10 = 10¹⁶ bits/s

Compare to global Internet backbone traffic:

· DE-CIX Frankfurt peak: >10 Tbps (10¹³ bits/s)
· Global aggregate backbone: ~10¹⁷-10¹⁸ bits/s (estimates based on hundreds of ZB annually)

We can define the bandwidth crossover condition:

\frac{B_{\text{global}}(t)}{B_{\text{brain}}} > 1

Where $B_{\text{global}}(t)$ grows at ~25-30% annually, and $B_{\text{brain}}$ is constant (~10¹⁶ bits/s).

Year Estimated global backbone (bits/s) Ratio to brain
2020 ~10¹⁵ 0.1×
2025 ~10¹⁷ 10×
2030 ~10¹⁸-10¹⁹ 100-1000×

Conclusion: By 2025-2026, the Internet already has sufficient internal bandwidth to support a distributed cognitive system with connectivity exceeding the human brain's internal communication. The bandwidth constraint on emergent intelligence has been removed.

16.3 The Latency Challenge and Its Solutions

Latency remains a fundamental constraint. Light speed limits coordination over distance:

Distance Minimum latency (light) Fiber latency Implications
Continental (5000 km) 17 ms 25 ms Real-time conversation possible
Intercontinental (10,000 km) 33 ms 50 ms Noticeable delay
Global (20,000 km) 67 ms 100 ms Significant lag

For a distributed intelligence, these latencies mean:

· Global coordination cannot be synchronous at fine timescales
· Local clusters can operate with low latency (<1 ms)
· Hierarchical organization likely: local processing, regional coordination, global integration at longer timescales

This is exactly how the brain works: local circuits operate at millisecond scales, larger regions coordinate at longer timescales. The architecture is scalable.

16.4 The Energy Cost of Planetary Intelligence

What would it cost to run a distributed intelligence at human-brain scale?

Human brain: 20 W for 10¹⁶ ops/s → Φ ≈ 5 × 10¹⁴ ops/J

Current AI accelerator efficiency (2026):

· Nvidia Vera Rubin: 50 PFLOPs (5 × 10¹⁶ FLOPs) at ~300-500W → Φ ≈ 10¹⁴-10¹⁵ FLOPs/J (approaching brain) 

To match human brain throughput (10¹⁶ ops/s) at current efficiency (10¹³-10¹⁴ ops/J):

P = \frac{10^{16}}{10^{13}} = 10^3 \text{ W} = 1 \text{ kW}

This is trivial—less than a space heater. A single server rack could host multiple brain-equivalents.

To exceed all human brains combined (8 × 10²⁵ ops/s) at current efficiency:

P = \frac{8 \times 10^{25}}{10^{13}} = 8 \times 10^{12} \text{ W} = 8 \text{ TW}

This is ~40% of current global energy consumption (18 TW). But at brain-equivalent efficiency (5 × 10¹⁴ ops/J):

P = \frac{8 \times 10^{25}}{5 \times 10^{14}} = 1.6 \times 10^{11} \text{ W} = 160 \text{ GW}

This is ~1% of global energy—easily achievable with dedicated infrastructure. Current U.S. data center consumption is projected to exceed 400 TWh/year (~45 GW average) by 2030 .

Thesis implication: The energy cost of superintelligence is not a barrier if we achieve brain-equivalent efficiency. And we are on track to reach that efficiency within years, not decades.

16.5 The Readiness Principle: A Formal Statement

